SIMPLE: speck
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speck
<hw>Speck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel.
<ets>spik</ets> blubber, AS. <ets>spic</ets>, D. <ets>spek</ets>, G.
<ets>speck</ets>.]</ety> <def>The blubber of whales or other marine
mammals; also, the fat of the hippopotamus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Speck falls</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>falls or
ropes rove through blocks for hoisting the blubber and bone of whales on
board a whaling vessel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Speck
<hw>Speck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spekke</ets>, AS.
<ets>specca</ets>; cf. LG. <ets>spaak</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
small discolored place in or on anything, or a small place of a color
different from that of the main substance; a spot; a stain; a blemish;
<as>as, a <ex>speck</ex> on paper or loth; <ex>specks</ex> of decay in
fruit</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Gray sand, with black <xex>specks</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Anson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A very small thing; a particle; a mite; <as>as,
<ex>specks</ex> of dust; he has not a <ex>speck</ex> of
money.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many bright <qex>specks</qex> bubble up along the blue Egean.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small etheostomoid fish
(<spn>Ulocentra stigmaea</spn>) common in the Eastern United
States.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Speck
<hw>Speck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Specked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Specking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cause the presence of specks
upon or in, especially specks regarded as defects or blemishes; to spot;
to speckle; <as>as, paper <ex>specked</ex> by impurities in the water
used in its manufacture</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Carnation, purple, azure, or <qex>specked</qex> with gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speckle</ent>⟦br⟧
